When I write in my livejournal, I take little to no regard as to who may read it, as doing so greatly discourages me from writing anything at all.


I found myself writing this in Microsoft Word because I was too afraid of what everyone might think or say, and of what Dan might think or say, but I've decided to put it in anyways


If I could play college football, on a semi competitive level, that would be my dream.  To be great.  To understand the game.  To run with vision.  To catch all the passes I can.  To run as fast as I can.  To be considered a competitive player.  To be a Wide Receiver.  Not for glamour, or pride, or money.  But to accomplish that.  To be that.  To race against everything that says I can't or shouldn't, to race so fast that I finish.

Sunday night I go to be interviewed by the bishop to see if I am fit to be ordained an Elder.  


I want to serve a mission, not because I think it will be fun, but because I think it will be right.


...but it makes sense to me

I think life is full of events, or of course it is, but, maybe only for me, maybe not for anyone else, life is like a 2-room building.  You sit in 1 room for an hour.  And then you open the door to the other room, and immediately get punched in the face.  You then quickly close the door, and sit for another hour.  You're always going to get punched in the face no matter what.  Every hour on the hour.  It's not the circumstances that change, really, it's how you change to them.  Everyone is going to have trials.  Everyone is going to have ups and downs.  One cannot rid themselves of difficulties.  They can only rise above them.  Now I'm not really suffering any great trials at the moment.  But the small ones that I encounter make me realize that the big ones are just more drawn out, or only bigger because I tell myself they are.    

So I suppose my most recent equation for success would be to do the best you can, and let God take care of the rest.  I'll see if it works.

Youth Conference was incredibly painful, and thoroughly awesome.  Sometime during testimony meeting, when no one was looking, the spirit came down, in one abrupt wave, and engulfed us all.  It was everywhere.  It's like being raised up on a platform above earth.  I have never had such an experience with such an amazing group of people.  To spend so much time with a person like Brody or Christine makes you realize what kind of person you're supposed to be, or not being.  

Ruth gets married friday.

I have two songs to go on expert in Guitar Hero.

NFL preseason starts next month.

I want to go back to Youth Conference.

In short God>Man.

Sometimes you don't know what to do.

And then, it turns out you really do know what to do, but you really don't want to do it.  But you have to do it, because you were too afraid to do what you should have done earlier, but its too late for that now.  

I bought Guitar Hero, and its the most incredibly addictive game of this generation.  The music and the images on the screen release a primal urge, to continue the song in absolute  perfection.  

If school had this kind of rhythm, the Ivy League would be 150 schools large, and cd's like "American Idiot" wouldn't be released.  Maybe we should integrate Led Zeppelin and flashing lights into our Math classes.    

Or maybe math is not all that important, because it doesn't promote creative thinking, which is necessary for humankind to function properly.



I'm going to ______________ every day.


Fill in the blank.

Ok.  I've got a story to tell.  I get off work, its 10:31.  Look at the car, notice the windshield wipers are up, "thats strange", I think to myself.  I put the keys into the admission, turn the keys, the car makes a strange noise, nothing happens. I repeat this process several times, to no avail.  I quickly determine that I foolishly left my windshield wipers on during my 5-hour work shift, which would explain why the battery is dead.  I call home, phone is  in use.  I leave a message.  I call back a few more times, and then my phone runs out of minutes.  Attempts to put more minutes on the phone fail miserably.  Plan to walk down to Hess to buy Top-up card fails, results in plan to buy Sprite Zero and Protein Bar.  Plan to abandon car and walk home aborted quickly as it was cold and wet and Middletown. Plan to sleep in back of car and hope parents come find me commenced.  Noticed people coming out of side exit.  I proceed to bang violently on the side exit, shortly thereafter Amy comes to the door.  I tell her of my situation, tells me I can use the phone.  She then says aloud, "I think Chris has jumper cables.  Lets ask him."  Chris had jumper cables.  I got home by 12, and determined to buy Chris a small land mass off the coast of Indonesia.  That plan still has details to sort out.  But before I left, Chris said something.  I don't know how he meant it, but I know how I understood it.  

He said    "Always be prepared"

Recently, I found myself reading the scriptures and happened upon a particular scripture that caused me to think "I should put that in my profile, or in my livejournal".  I do not remember which scripture that is.  Upon searching for it, I came upon a most peculiar problem.  All of the verses that I was reading seemed to have particular importance and meaning, the scriptures were seemingly brimming with genius.  I have never found such meaning in so many passages in such a small period of time.

I never found the original scripture, but this one will do for now.

Moroni 7:33

And Christ hath said: If ye will have faith in me ye shall have power to do whatsoever thing is expedient in me.
Remember everyone, keep the big picture in mind.

I've applied to the Community College of Rhode Island
I've applied to Bristol Community College
I've applied to Cal State - Monterey Bay
I've applied to Cal State - Sacramento

Now all I've to do is graduate, and wait.
And then there is the little decision of where to go to school.
My declared major is computer science.  I don't know anything about computers.  I chose Computer Science, not because I'm looking forward to trying implant JAVA in my brain, but because I didn't know  what else to do.  I could've picked english.  But then I wouldn't know what to do with an english degree.  I'm minoring in English instead.  

I recently applied to Holiday Cinemas, the sign said they needed someone to work nights and weekends, which is good, cause I need to work.  

In case you thought I had shed all of my nerdy inhibitions and became a responsible individual, this is the new piece of hardware I am now drooling over - http://www.n-sider.com/media/news-2006-03-20-nintendodslite.jpg

now you may ask yourself.  Doesn't Dave already have a DS?  The answer is, of course, Yes.  I have three games I rarely play for it.  So why would I want this?  I couldn't possibly describe any good reason to spend another 150 on something I already have.  I probably won't buy it, because I don't buy anything, and I want to go to college.  But that won't stop me from drooling.


Oh, and get Guitar Hero.  Everyone buy Guitar Hero.  If you don't have a playstation 2, buy one, then get Guitar Hero.  I don't care who you are.  Buy it.  It's the new way to play games, not lost in a sea of complication and depth of detail and character development, but for the fun and draw of playing.  Not since the glory days of the Super Nintendo have I been drawn to a game so compulsively.  It's where games originated, not from a new world to create yourself in, but to play.  To enjoy a game.  Not to work to level up.  That's a new concept huh.

I want to write.  I want to become a writer.  That's what I want to do, I want to write.  I don't care if I get weak grades on my writing assignments, I like to write, and therefore have the potential to excel at writing.  I don't know what area of writing I intend to aim for.  My writing which comes from my thoughts, are very unable to focus on one concept for very long.  

Nine days and counting until the release of Elder Scrolls IV: Oblivion for the Xbox 360 and the PC.  The game comes out 5 days before my Rough Draft for the English Paper on the symbolic nature of the various humanoid characters from the christianity-influenced Chronicles of Narnia. 

English, save Junior year, has consistently been my favorite subject.  Right now we're reading a little-known piece that perhaps you've heard of...........Catcher in the Rye. The main character, Holden Caulfield is quite the potty-mouth if I must say so myself. Upon reading the novel (book, I don't know if its a novel) the author quickly mentions a certain practice as unholy, as "whoring" even.  I am referring to the shameless practice of selling out the themes, characters and story of a great novel and letting it be transformed, downsized, reduced(dare I say) to a made for tv(quality) movie for the purpose of financial empowerment.  The Lord of the Rings series of movies are an obvious exception, seeing as how Mr. Jackson knew an army of raging sword-and-shield fantasy fanatics would storm his homestead and rapidly proceed to burn and pillage his livelihood as well as his loved ones if the movie(s) were not several times more glorious than previously thought possible (which of course they were).  

I recently attended Priest/Laurel conference under the belief that doing so would bring me ever closer to a high-paying (minimum wage) job.  I was enthralled by the experience.  I re-acquainted myself with Mr. Jon Ward.  How quickly had I forgotten how hilariously awesome the young man is in so many ways.  I visited his freshly created website...www.storminmormon.net and found myself thoroughly amused.

It seems to me that the mistakes I make are small in variety, and great in number.  I simply forget too quickly, such as man so often does.  So please, if you find me stumbling about without direction, please do as my parents have done and remind me where to go.

There's always hope for next year.
